    "what_description": "Acacia fasciculata is a shrub or small tree species belonging to the family Fabaceae. It is characterized by its slender branches, often bearing leafy branchlets and spines. The leaves are bipinnate, with 2-6 pairs of pinnae, each pinna having 4-10 pairs of leaflets, with leaflets being lanceolate and 10-20 mm long. The flowers are yellow or creamy, in axillary spikes, with calyx tubular and 1-1.5 mm long, and corolla 4-merous and 3-4 mm long. Acacia fasciculata is native to Australia, where it grows in sandy or stony soils, often in scrubland or open forest.",
